timeseries.models.arima

Class Arima

  • java.lang.Object
    • timeseries.models.arima.Arima
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Model

    public final class Arima
extends Object
implements Model
    A seasonal autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) model. This class is immutable and thread-safe.

    • Nested Class Summary

      Nested Classes 
      Modifier and Type Class and Description
      static class  Arima.FittingStrategy
      The strategy to be used for fitting an ARIMA model.
      static class  Arima.ModelCoefficients
      Consists of the autoregressive and moving-average coefficients for a seasonal ARIMA model, along with the degrees of differencing and the model mean.
      static class  Arima.ModelOrder
      The order of an ARIMA model, consisting of the number of autoregressive and moving average parameters, along with the degree of differencing and a flag indicating whether or not the model includes a constant.
      static class  Arima.Simulation
      An ARIMA model simulation.

      • model

        public static Arima model(TimeSeries observations,
                          Arima.ModelOrder order,
                          TimePeriod seasonalCycle)
        Create a new ARIMA model from the given observations, model order, and seasonal cycle. This method sets the model Arima.FittingStrategy to unconditional sum-of-squares.
        Parameters:
        observations - the time series of observations.
        order - the order of the ARIMA model.
        seasonalCycle - the amount of time it takes for the seasonal pattern to complete one cycle. For example, monthly data usually has a cycle of one year, hourly data a cycle of one day, etc... However, a seasonal cycle may be an arbitrary amount of time.
        Returns:
        a new ARIMA model from the given observations, model order, and seasonal cycle.

      • model

        public static Arima model(TimeSeries observations,
                          Arima.ModelOrder order,
                          Arima.FittingStrategy fittingStrategy)
        Create a new ARIMA model from the given observations, model order, and fitting strategy. This method sets the seasonal cycle to one year.
        Parameters:
        observations - the time series of observations.
        order - the order of the ARIMA model.
        fittingStrategy - the strategy to use to fit the model to the data. Maximum-likelihood estimates are typically preferred for greater precision and accuracy, but take longer to obtain than conditional or unconditional sum-of-squares estimates. Unconditional sum-of-squares tends to be more accurate, more precise, and quicker to obtain than conditional sum-of-squares.
        Returns:
        a new ARIMA model from the given observations, model order, and fitting strategy.

        fittingStrategy - the strategy to use to fit the model to the data. Maximum-likelihood estimates are typically preferred for greater precision and accuracy, but take longer to obtain than conditional or unconditional sum-of-squares estimates. Unconditional sum-of-squares tends to be more accurate, more precise, and quicker to obtain than conditional sum-of-squares.

                                     int d,
                                     int q,
                                     int P,
                                     int D,
                                     int Q)
        Create a new ModelOrder using the provided number of autoregressive and moving-average parameters, as well as the degrees of differencing. A constant will be fit only if both d and D are equal to 0.
        Parameters:
        p - the number of non-seasonal autoregressive coefficients.
        d - the degree of non-seasonal differencing.
        q - the number of non-seasonal moving-average coefficients.
        P - the number of seasonal autoregressive coefficients.
        D - the degree of seasonal differencing.
        Q - the number of seasonal moving-average coefficients.
        Returns:
        a new ARIMA model order.

                                     boolean constant)
        Create a new ModelOrder using the provided number of autoregressive and moving-average parameters, as well as the degrees of differencing and indication of whether or not to fit a constant.

      • forecast

        public Forecast forecast(int steps,
                         double alpha)
        Description copied from interface: Model
        Produce a new forecast up to the given number of steps with the given α significance level for computing prediction intervals.
        Specified by:
        forecast in interface Model
        Parameters:
        steps - the number of time periods ahead to forecast.
        alpha - the probability that a future observation will fall outside the associated (1 - α)100% prediction interval, given that the model is "correct". Note that the correctness of the model often comes with a high degree of uncertainty and this should be taken into account when making decisions. In other words, the provided prediction intervals will often be overly optimistic.
        Returns:
        a new forecast up to the given number of steps ahead with the given significance level.
